The Sam wrote:Ge0ph wrote:The only time I've even seen a gun in the past 10 to 15 years is when it's strapped onto an officer of the law. I'm not going to try to take it from him just to see if it's loaded. Gun nuts who thinks everybody should be a gun nut drives me nuts.You obviously have a personal thing with guns. You don't like 'em, and I respect that. I'm not a gun nut and I'm not advocating that you should be one either. I'm not saying that everyone should know how to shoot a gun, or take one apart and clean it, or learn to tell the difference between various weapons and types of ammunition. All I'm saying is that it doesn't hurt to know how to disable a potentially dangerous piece of equipment that's relatively common place (even in countries without a "gun culture"). Your example of taking a gun from an LEO to check if it's loaded is obviously hyperbole. But you don't know if you might one day find yourself in a situation where a firearm is present and no one else is present that can disable it.I'm not saying that everyone should be FORCED to learn these things, obviously. I'm just saying that, in my opinion, it's a useful piece of information that--even if in an extremely unlikely range of scenarios--might prove life-saving. That's all.I'm not against guns, in fact when ever I hear of someone pushing a law to prohibit gun ownership I get really pissed. I don't want to own a gun but don't tell me I can't. The LEO example was my poor attempt at a joke. However, the odds me needing to know any such thing about guns are very slim. I do get offended when someone thinks I should learn about something they are into but I just don't give two shits about.
