Jakal wrote:dracusoara wrote:Bravehamster wrote:hux wrote:Bravehamster wrote:A man should be able to change a diaper, plan an invasion, butcher a hog, con a ship, design a building, write a sonnet, balance accounts, build a wall, set a bone, comfort the dying, take orders, give orders, cooperate, act alone, solve equations, analyze a new problem, pitch manure, program a computer, cook a tasty meal, fight efficiently, die gallantly. Specialization is for insects. -Heinlein Lazarus LongFTFY.You just committed one of my pet hates: attributing a quote to the author when in fact it's something said by a particular character in a particular context. In this case, Lazarus Long is a man who lives for more than 2,000 years, drifts from planet to planet, and hates regimented lifestyles. To someone like that, the above list might seem like obvious sense. To the average human with a ~75-80 year lifespan, living in modern day western society, however, probably not so much.So, yeah, my "Stuff you really ought to know" list just got expanded by one: How to assess the motivation of fictional characters and, thus, evaluate what they're saying. I'd agree with you, except Heinlein said it himself in a commencement address. So Doesn't make him any less wrong.Fuck that weakass shit. The fact that most people are too complacent/incompetent/etc to develop and maintain a well-rounded skillset is not a valid point favoring the acceptability of being a "specialized" ponce who worthlessly flops around like a dead fish whenever nudged out of their 9-5 rat race. If only life was simple enough to specialize. Most techies spend their lives sitting at a cube and typing away for someone twenty years their junior who's busy making it rain while doing lines of blow off hookers. Someone's gotta do the bitch work, so I'm not about to shittalk that path in life, but it leaves deskmonkeys in a very poor position to hate on anyone who had what it takes to do more with their lives. Heinlein isn't talking about the "average human." The "average human" is a fucking joke whom the Lounge mocks daily for driving in the passing lane, putting ketchup on steak, watching Fox news, leaftycausting, and teaching creationism in schools. Heinlein is talking about a Man. The polymath "Renaissance Man" isn't some imaginary, impossible ideal. We have regulars here who are doctor-soldiers. We have regulars who simultaneously build houses, program computers, and hunt what they eat, all while singlehandedly raising kids. We have regulars here who design tools which save the lives of people you care about, we have regulars who design weapons to hurt the people who want to hurt you, we have regulars who teach special forces types their asskicking mcguyver skills, and they may very well be the same damn person.I'll be the first to admit that not everyone can be expected to simultaneously grant, change, and take life, but anyone claiming pursuit, possession, or application of a skillset necessary to do these things is somehow "wrong" will be looked upon with nothing but contempt, scorn, and disgust by those who embody the ideal Heinlein challenges humanity to achieve.While the "average human" can get by with a willfully limited skillset, such individuals make no lasting impact on society and are ultimately forgotten.All those examples you gave? Those people have done what they've done because they specialized to do what they're doing. DP trained and specialized as a Marine, then as a medic. He also does other things, and I'd bet he does them well. But ask him to make bread from scratch: plow and sew a field, know what it takes to grow several types of grain, know when to harvest, reap the crop, separate the grains, grind the grains to make flour, then make bread. After all, feeding yourself is an important part of life, and he's not your idea of the "average human," so he should be able to do it right? I'd bet money that he wouldn't be able to do it right now. Tom Foolery is also awesome, he's done a lot in terms of house building, child rearing, he could hunt a meal for sure, and has done various other impressive things. He's good at what he does, and he's good at other things, but I'm pretty sure if you put a bunch of unspun wool in front of him and asked him to produce a sweater, he wouldn't be able to. Being able to clothe yourself is important to life, but hey look, your second example of the ubermensch would fail at that. We all specialize. The ability to work as a society and to specialize is what has allowed us to achieve the things we have. If we didn't specialize we'd all be too busy trying to eek out survival to do anything beyond that. You seem to view specialization as meaning "I will do one thing, and one thing only for the rest of my life and never look beyond that." I think this view of specialization is wrong. Sure there are some people who do that, but most of the people I know are proficient in multiple areas, usually broken down by "work" and "hobbies." Most people I know have multiple hobbies, and are very invested in them and doing them well. And for work, most people grow in their careers, learning more, sometimes in the same field sometimes outside. This might seem to you to mean that these people don't specialize. I would bet that most smart people with multiple skills in various fields, if put on a desert island with a knife and a flint, will not be able to survive very long. Due to the time they've had to spend acquiring the skills they have, they did not spend any time on basic survival skills, because they have not had to. I don't need to know how an internal combustion engine works, and be able to build and maintain one, to drive a car. You don't need to know how to brew up a batch of enzymes and what surfactants and chemicals to mix together to get your clothes clean. John Doe down the street doesn't need to know how to produce analgesics to make his headache go away. If we all had to know everything, we'd all know nothing, especially as there are more and more scientific and technological discoveries that it becomes prohibitive to learn and know everything. I'm not advocating ignorance, or saying that people shouldn't strive to better themselves. I am saying that "specialization is for insects" is a fucking dumb thing to say, a statement that ignores the way society works and how we got to be so advanced.
Major General Thanatos
